\par Short Description:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn This document describes how to create monsters, and explains in brief how the various weapon and armour values interact. Before reading this document you should read the {\i object.doc}
 document describing weapon and armour quality. Abilities and their meaning is described in the {\i ability.doc} document.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par I\rquote ve attempted to remove all old references that are no longer valid (hand, toughness, etc).
\par \pard \qj\li720\keep\keepn\tx-1560 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\b\fs40\lang2057 2.\tab}\pard\plain \s1\qc\sa360\keep\keepn\pagebb{\*\pn \pnlvl1\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 {\pntxta .}}\b\f4\fs40\lang2057 Introduction
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 This document will step-by-step go through the most important attributes of a monster and explain their meaning.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.1\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 Monster Level ({\i level})
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 When creating a monster it must be bet
ween level 0 and 199. The level of the monster decides how many skill points and ability points the monster has. Players start at third level and are expected to be between level [3..100]. The level of the monster is specified using the level field.

\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \tab level 0\tab \tab /* Mosquito */
\par 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn In general, an area should be designed around a 10 level span to be fairly consistent. For example a goblin camp for newbie players should be of level 0-10 (perhaps only 6). An orc area might be in the range 10-20th level.
\par The reason i
s, that monsters 10 levels below a player give 0 experience points while monsters 10 levels above a player are beginning to be a difficult kill. If you make an area too diverse players will give up since monsters either seem too easy (no experience) or to
o hard.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.2\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 Natural armour & attack
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 The natural armour is specified using the NATURAL_DEF macro together with natural attack. For example:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par NATURAL_DEF(WPN_CRUSH, ARM_PLATE)
\par 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn You should know that the {\i weight }of the monster determines the maximum amount of damage it can give when using a natural attack. The weight is categorized as follows:
