\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn By default monsters are medium.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.3\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 Good, Evil and Neutral alignments ({\i alignment})
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 
Alignment is a value between -1000 and +1000, where -1000 is ultimate evil, 0 is neutral and +1000 is ultimate good. Good is per definition any value from +1000..+350, neutral is any value from +349..-349 and evil is any value from -350..-1000. Any value 
in between can also be used.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn \tab alignment -750\tab /* Quite evil, maybe a Ghoul\tab */
\par \tab alignment -350\tab /* Barely evil.\tab \tab \tab */
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.4\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 The Race ({\i race})
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 Each monster has a race as specified in {\i values.h}. In case you can\rquote t find a race which matches your monster, just use #define RACE_XXX in you own zonefile with a number that isn\rquote 
t already used. We will then later transfer it to values.h. Example:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \tab race RACE_DRAGON_SILVER
\par 
\par or if the race you need isn\rquote t defined, you could type:
\par 
\par \tab #define RACE_CRABMAN\tab 7681\tab /* This is a large red crab man */
\par \tab race RACE_CRABMAN
\par 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn Later it will be inserted into values.h - and you should then remove your definition (you will get warnings at that time).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.5\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 The gender ({\i sex})
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 Each monster has a gender: male, female or none, as specified in {\i values.h} SEX_XXX macros. Example:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn \tab sex SEX_NEUTRAL
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.6\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 Setting Abilities ({\i ability[]})
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 All abilities are in the range [1..200]. Players usually have a maximum of 150, modified by magic... 200 is considered divine.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn When creating a monster you can not directly specify the size of the abilities, instead you specify a percentage distribution of points. The amount of points are then distributed by the computer according to {\i the specified level}
. The MSET_ABILITY macro is available for this purpose, and has the format:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \tab MSET_ABILITY(str,dex,con,hpp,bra,cha,mag,div)
\par 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
The amount of points distributed depends directly upon the level of the monster and the percentage as the table below shows. If for example you create a monsters of level 30, then 20% will cause the monster to get a little above 30 points.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn Note that the sum of the ability values must be 100%. This is thus an example of an ability distribution:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \tab MSET_ABILITY(25,15,10,15,10,5,10,0)  /* Sum is 100% */
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs30\lang2057 2.6.1\tab}\pard\plain \s3\sb240\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl3\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 {\pntxtb .}}\f4\fs30\lang2057 \page Hints
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 If you choose high percentages and high levels, you may \ldblquote waste\rdblquote 
 a ability points as it would pop above 200 (all excess points are simply removed). For example a level 199 monster with an ability percentage a bit above 20% will make an ability above the 200 points maximum.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn Do not spend points on both MAG and DIV, {\i only the appropriate value of the two are used}. So magic users should have MAG (fireball, etc.) and clerics should have DIV (cure light wounds, etc.).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.7\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 Setting Weapon and Spell skills ({\i spell[], weapon[]})
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 NPC's know about weapons and spells but not at the same detailed level as the player. For NPC\rquote s the spell and weapon group are used. Thus the \ldblquote axe hammer category\rdblquote 
 defines all defence and all attack for all kind of axes and hammers - whereas the player would have to train individually in each axe and hammer type. The same is true for spells. Th
us if a monster has 25 points in the weapon "sword category" it will fight (and defend) with all sword-like weapons at skill 25.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn When you define weapon and spell skills (monsters have no skill skills) you also define these as percentages, and the program automatically distributes the points. Use the pre-defined macros:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \tab MSET_WEAPON(axe_ham, sword, club_mace, polearm, unarmed, special)
\par 
\par Where
\par \tab {\i axe_ham}\tab Is any hammer or axe weapon.
\par \tab {\i sword}\tab \tab Is any sword like weapon, including dagger and rapier, etc.
\par \tab {\i club_mace}\tab Is any club or mace like weapon, flails, morning star, etc.
\par \pard \qj\fi-2127\li2127\keep\keepn\tx709 {\i \tab polearm}\tab Is any flail or pole like weapon: spear, staff, halberd, trident, sickle, scythe.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn \tab {\i unarmed}\tab Is any bite, claw, sting or other natural attack.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn \tab {\i special}\tab Is any very peculiar weapon, currently only whip.
\par 
\par \tab MSET_SPELL(div, pro, det, sum, cre, min, hea, col, cel, int, ext)
\par 
\par Where
\par \tab {\i div}\tab Covers all divine sphere spell.
\par \tab {\i pro}\tab Covers all protection sphere spells.
\par \tab {\i det}\tab Covers all detection sphere spells.
\par \tab {\i sum}\tab Covers all summoning spells.
\par \tab {\i cre}\tab Covers all creation spells.
\par \tab {\i min}\tab Covers all mind spells.
\par \tab {\i hea}\tab Covers all heat spells (fireball, etc.)
\par \tab {\i col}\tab Covers all cold spells (frostball, etc.)
\par \tab {\i cel}\tab Covers all cell (electricity) spells (jolt, lightning bolt, etc.)
\par \tab {\i int}\tab Covers all internal (poison) spells (toxicate, etc.)
\par \tab {\i ext}\tab Covers all external (acid) spells (acid ball etc.)
\par See also {\i values.h} and {\i wmacros.h}.
\par The sum of all spell and weapon skills must be 100%. For example, the sum is 100%:
\par 
\par   \tab MSET_WEAPON(10,10,20,5,15,5)\tab /* 75% Total, Club/Mace is primary\tab */
\par \tab MSET_SPELL(8,0,0,3,0,3,2,3,3,3,3)\tab /* 25% Total, Fire is primary\tab \tab */
\par 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
Remember that the groups define both attack and defence. Thus if you make an Orc which has 0% in the flail group it can only use its dexterity to defend itself. Likewise with spell groups. For this reason the groups are both "resistance" as well as attack
 groups.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.8\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 Spell casting monsters
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 Some monsters are spell casting and spend a lot of points on either Magic or Divine power together with brain. To make a monster cast spells a number of various special routines are available, for example:

\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \tab special SFUN_COMBAT_MAGIC \ldblquote cast acid ball\rdblquote 
\par \tab special SFUN_COMBAT_MAGIC_HEAL \ldblquote cast random teleport\rdblquote 
\par 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn This would make a monster use the \ldblquote acid ball\rdblquote  spell when engaged in combat. The monster would attempt to cast \ldblquote random teleport\rdblquote 
 when it gets low on hitpoints. The following table shows which spells a monster should use at a given level:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
