\b\cf8 Circle\cell }\pard \intbl {\b\cf8 \row }\trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \clcfpat16\clcbpat8\clshdng2000 \cellx984\clcfpat16\clcbpat8\clshdng2000 \cellx3072 \pard \qj\keep\keepn\intbl 0-14\cell \pard \qj\keep\keepn\intbl 1st magic circle\cell \pard 
\intbl \row \pard \qj\keep\keepn\intbl 15-34\cell \pard \qj\keep\keepn\intbl 2nd magic circle\cell \pard \intbl \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \clbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw30\brdrcf15 \cellx984\clbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw30\brdrcf15 \cellx3072 \pard 
\qj\keep\keepn\intbl 35-200\cell \pard \qj\keep\keepn\intbl 3rd magic circle\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn For example, a fireusing monster of
 level 20 would use the 2nd circle of magic (the fireball spell) whereas a level 5 monster would use the burn spell. There are also special routines for breathweapons for use with for example dragons. See monster definitions in {\i composed.h}.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs36\lang2057 2.9\tab}\pard\plain \s2\qj\sb360\sa120\keep\keepn{\*\pn \pnlvl2\pndec\pnprev1\pnstart1\pnsp144 }\f4\fs36\lang2057 More or less Experience ({\i exp})
\par \pard\plain \qj\keep\keepn \f4\fs26\lang2057 By default a monster gives the amount of experience it is worth (which depends on the {\i level}
 of the monster). If you create a particular powerful monster or a very weak monster, you may wish to raise or lower the amount of experience given to the player. This can be done by specifying an experience percentage modification.
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn 
You may want to modify the standard amount (of 0%) when you create non-standard monsters. The default amount is not always the correct amount, for example an aggressive invisible 10th level dragon with breath weapon and spells, should give more exp than a
 blind, thieves-friendly dragon. The way I suggest you to calculate the monsters experience value should be adding the following amplifiers:
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn Note that if the monster is using wands, scrolls, staffs or magical items this should {\i not }increase the exp amount, since the item value should be more than enough reward for the players!
\par \pard \qj\keep\keepn See example application later in this document.
